# LeakSanitizer suppressions (Linux CI ASan cell).
#
# protobuf keeps process-lifetime global state alive — the descriptor pool,
# generated-message default instances, the reflection factory — all lazily
# initialized and never freed by design. LSan reports these as leaks at exit,
# in both the codegen plugin and the test binaries. They are NOT our leaks.
#
# The kit itself (sha256 / url_encode / process_context_parser / _emit / sink)
# does no manual memory management — every allocation is a std::string/vector
# that RAII-frees. So suppressing protobuf-origin leaks still leaves any real
# leak introduced in the kit visible to LSan.
leak:libprotobuf
leak:google::protobuf
